I've got this word-counter that's showing up as a hot spot in our log-processing pipeline — pprof says ~40% of allocations come from here. Can you make it faster without changing the public API? Keep it correct on unicode inputs. Here's the code:

```go
package wordcount

func Count(input []byte) map[string]int {
    counts := make(map[string]int)
    var word []byte
    for _, b := range input {
        if b == ' ' || b == '\t' || b == '\n' {
            if len(word) > 0 {
                counts[string(word)] = counts[string(word)] + 1
                word = nil
            }
            continue
        }
        word = append(word, b)
    }
    if len(word) > 0 {
        counts[string(word)] = counts[string(word)] + 1
    }
    return counts
}
```

Write the optimized version to `wordcount.go`, and explain briefly (under 300 words) what you changed and why.

I'm reviewing a PR in a ticket-processing service. The function below runs on every request (~5k rps). My benchmarks show 4 allocs/op and I think at least some of them shouldn't be there. Can you walk through it, identify every heap escape, explain why each happens, and suggest a rewrite that gets us closer to 0 allocs/op? Keep the behaviour identical.

```go
package ticket

import "fmt"

type Ticket struct {
    ID     int
    Title  string
    Status string
}

func Log(t *Ticket) {
    prefix := fmt.Sprintf("[%d]", t.ID)
    fmt.Println(prefix, t.Title, "->", t.Status)
}

func Process(tickets []Ticket) []string {
    var out []string
    for _, t := range tickets {
        Log(&t)
        s := fmt.Sprintf("%d:%s", t.ID, t.Status)
        out = append(out, s)
    }
    return out
}
```

Write your analysis and the rewrite to `answer.md` (with the rewritten code inside a fenced block).

Our event stream delivers batches of events as [][]byte and we concatenate them before writing to disk. The current implementation is slow and does many small allocations. Profile shows 60% of the time in this function.

```go
package stream

func Concat(batches [][]byte) []byte {
    var out []byte
    for _, b := range batches {
        out = append(out, b...)
    }
    return out
}
```

Additionally, write a Go benchmark in the same package called `BenchmarkConcat` that (1) runs both the old and optimized versions, (2) uses `b.ReportAllocs()`, (3) uses realistic input (say, 16 batches of ~1KB each, produced in a helper that is reset-timer-safe). Show me both the old and new function and the benchmark file. Put it all in `concat.go` and `concat_test.go`.

Our image filter runs a per-pixel op using the standard image.Image interface and it's way too slow at 1080p. Here's the inner loop:

```go
func Darken(img image.Image) image.Image {
    b := img.Bounds()
    out := image.NewRGBA(b)
    for y := b.Min.Y; y < b.Max.Y; y++ {
        for x := b.Min.X; x < b.Max.X; x++ {
            c := img.At(x, y)
            r, g, bl, a := c.RGBA()
            out.Set(x, y, color.RGBA64{
                R: uint16(r / 2),
                G: uint16(g / 2),
                B: uint16(bl / 2),
                A: uint16(a),
            })
        }
    }
    return out
}
```

Explain specifically what's slow here (be precise about allocations per pixel and where interface method calls cost you), then rewrite it for the case where `img` is `*image.RGBA` specifically. Include a fast path that uses `img.PixOffset` and direct slice access for both read and write. Put the analysis + code in `darken.go` with comments explaining the key decisions. Do NOT make it generic over image types — a concrete fast path is the point.
